Solution: redirected you too many times when creating user authentication check in global middleware

2023.05.16 by Murad Shaker

Sometimes, when creating a project using Laravel, you may encounter many direct and indirect problems. Therefore, programmers must be patient and flexible in facing these problems in order to find solutions and continue in this profession. One of these problems is when building an authentication system that verifies in middleware whether the user is logged in or not. A hidden issue may appear on the browser when running the project, saying "Too many redirects The cause of this problem:: is the frequent redirects caused by middleware

Now we start explaining

You may notice that everything seems normal and no problems have arisen. However, if you create an account and log in, you may encounter an issue: when you log in and are redirected to the index file, the problem is that you can go back to the login and registration pages without logging out

-----------------------------

Now, due to the lack of an authentication system, we need to create an authentication system to verify in intermediary programs whether the user has logged in or not.

To create authentication, we must first add the model class name  ( UserModel ) that contains the user data table (usus) to the providers array inside the  Auth.php  file located in this directory config\auth.php
To make authentication have a role in verifying the user's authentication, we need to create middleware

Middleware is important as it protects your application from insecure requests or requests that need to be verified. It acts as a checkpoint for incoming requests.
You can understand it through this image:

 

 

You can set conditions, etc. in the middleware, depending on your application's needs
-------------------------
Thus, I will utilize  global middleware  to verify whether the user is currently logged in or not

 php artiaan make:middleware AuthLoginMiddleware 
After creating the middleware, we now need to register the global middleware in the  Kernel.php  file. Go to this file located in this directory app\Http\Kernel.php and register the middleware in the 'middlewareGroups' array,
as shown in the image below.

Note:  that the global middleware should be registered inside the arrays  ( $middlewareGroups = [] )  or  ( $middleware= [] )

Let's now put the user authentication verification codes inside the global middleware. To do so,  Add the following lines

view source
print?
01public function handle(Request $request, Closure $next): Response
02 {
03     if(!Auth::check())
04     {                         
05         $redirect_to = 'login';             
06          return redirect($redirect_to);
07      }
08     }
09     return $next($request);
10 }

Let's try to see what happens:
Copy this link http://127.0.0.1:8000/login and paste it into your browser's URL bar. Then press the 'Enter' button.
You should have received a message by now,

as shown in the picture

We have now reached the crux of the matter.
This problem is caused by frequent redirects caused by middlewaer
The cause of this problem is the frequent redirections caused by the middleware through this  redirect()  function,
 as shown in the image

Now, when the project is run on the browser, this will happen behind the scenes like this.

For the first time when running the project on the browser at the link http://127.0.0.1:8000/login, in this case:

  1. The condition inside the middleware is executed, and then the redirection is made to the "login" page.
  2. After the previous or first redirection to the "login" page, the condition inside the middleware is also executed and thus it will redirect to 'login' through the second redirection.
  3. After the previous or second redirection to the "login" page, the condition inside the middleware is also executed and thus it will redirect to 'login' through the third redirection.
  4. After the previous or third redirection to the "login" page, the condition inside the middleware is also executed and thus it will redirect to 'login' through the fourth redirection.
  5. This process repeats without stopping. Eventually, a warning or error message will appear on the browser indicating that there are too many multiple redirections.

Note: This happens behind the scenes.
-------------------
To solve this problem we must stop redirection

We need to add a condition that reads or executes the line   return redirect($redirect_to);   only in the first redirection, and when it is time for the second, third, or subsequent redirections, we skip the line   return redirect($redirect_to);  based on the condition that we will create in the following steps
To achieve this condition, Add the following lines

view source
print?
01$currentRequestedPath = $request->path();
02if(!Auth::check())
03{  
04    $previousRequestedPath = session('PathName');
05 
06    if($currentRequestedPath != $previousRequestedPath){
07        $redirect_to = 'login';
08        session()->put('PathName' , $currentRequestedPath);
09        return redirect($redirect_to);
10    }
11}

Don't worry, I'll explain this to you. First, understand what happens behind the scenes inside the middleware using these two images below

When we run the project for the first time on the 'login' page, this is what happens behind the scenes inside the middleware

As shown in the image above, from within middleware on the first redirect, the current path name is retrieved using the following line:

 $currentRequestedPath = $request->path(); 

The value of this variable will be "login". 

The previous path name, which is stored in the session, can be retrieved using the following line:

 $previousRequestedPath = session('PathName'); 

However, the value of this line will be empty on the first redirect, which is good because the  current path name ("login")  does not equal the  previous path name ("")   Therefore, the condition will be true  and the commands inside the curly braces will be executed.

The  current path name ("login")  will be saved in the session using the following line:

 session()->put('PathName' , $currentRequestedPath); 

And we will be redirected to the "login" page using the following line:
 return redirect($redirect_to);

You may ask: Why do we save the current path name in the session [ session('PathName') ]
In order for middleware programs to detect in the second, third, or subsequent redirects that the  current path name ("login")  is the same as the  previous path name ("login") . In this case the condition is false, so the commands inside the parentheses will be escaped, thus the line  return redirect ($ redirect_to)  is not executed,

as shown in the image

So, the (redirected you too many times) issue is completely resolved because the command causing this issue is  return redirect($redirect_to);   and is skipped on the second and subsequent redirects, based on the explanation provided above.

 

Now, when you run the project on the browser, the problem of multiple redirects never appears

However, there is something to be aware of now. You cannot navigate to the 'register' file, meaning that you cannot create a new account.
To correct this error, add these commands inside the curly brackets of the condition that checks for the symmetry of the paths

view source
print?
01switch($currentRequestedPath){
02    case 'register':
03        $redirect_to = 'register';
04    break;
05    case 'login':
06        $redirect_to = 'login';
07    break;
08    default:
09       $redirect_to = 'login';
10       $currentRequestedPath = '';
11}
12session()->put('PathName' , $currentRequestedPath);
13return redirect($redirect_to);

To be like this as shown in the picture

Don't worry, nothing has changed. We just added a switch and the previous steps are still effective.
If the variable $currentRequestedPath representing the current path, in ( the Switch function ) is equal to "Register", we will be redirected to the registration page without any problems:

It happens behind the scenes
return redirect('register');

Note :: that if you go to the "register" page, the scenario is currently calculated like the previous steps. Just imagine  that you are using the "register" page instead of "login" in the previous steps.

 

If the $currentRequestedPath variable is equal to "login", it will go to the "login" page.
Now you can go to the "Registration" page and you can create an account without any problems

 

You might say what is the use of ( case default ) inside switch

With the (default case) , we can impose constraints that contribute to the organization and realism of this project
Based on (default case) if you are not logged in and if you go to any path except "/register" and "/login" it will take you back to the "login" page eg: if you are not logged in and go to the "index" page You will be redirected directly to the "login" page because you are not logged in (as long as you are not logged in, you cannot go anywhere except "login" and "Register")

Note that you can remove this variable $currentRequestedPath = ' ';
As you wish, if you want to delete it, delete it, I added it as per my need
Doesn't mean anything. It simply prevents the paths from being stored in the session, other than the "login" and "register" paths,
Currently, you cannot create a new account or log in because the global middleware prevents access to the POST routes for registration and login
To correct this, block these two paths from global middleware as shown

Now when you want to create an account: When you have registered correctly, you will go directly to the 'login' page, but the 'Successful Registration' message does not appear on the 'login' page.

 

To correct this, go to the Controller file that we created  'AuthLoginMiddleware' 
Add this line:
 session()->put('PathName', 'login'); 
above the with() function inside the  RegisterUser function , as shown in the image.

 

You may say how this line solves this problem
 session()->put('PathName', 'login');

Good question: First, let me tell you why this problem occurs

Initially, when we click on the register button, in this case the  RegisterUser function  is called, and upon successful registration, we will be redirected to the 'login' page with a success message being sent to the 'login' page.

 session()->put('PathName', 'login');

return redirect('/login') -> with('message_Sre' , 'registration successful');

But focus on something important: when we are redirected from here to the "login" path, we will be redirected from within the middleware and not from the  RegisterUser function  because when we are redirected to any path, it is checked directly from within the global middleware, In this case, the success message does not appear because we will be redirected to the "Login" page with a line  return redirect('/login')  new , from within middleware, and we are not redirected from within the  RegisterUser function so the 'success message' does not appear because middleware does not contain with()
This scenario is done this way

And to correct that:: We need to create a plan - So that when we are redirected from within the  RegisterUser function, we will bypass the codes responsible for our redirection within the middleware. And to do that, I mentioned it above
Finally, there is something to do:
Add this condition in the else statement associated with the condition that checks if the user has been authenticated in the middleware

view source
print?
1$PathsRl = array('login' , 'register');
2if(in_array($currentRequestedPath , $PathsRl))
3{
4   return redirect('/index');
5 }

Let it be in this order

The purpose of these commands is to prevent us from accessing the 'Register' and 'Login' pages if we are already logged in and currently on the 'index' or any other page except for the pages ('Register', 'Login')
